  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study titled \"Programmed withdrawal of cilia maintenance followed by centriole capping leads to permanent cilia loss during cerebellar granule cell neurogenesis\" has garnered significant attention, with a total of 13 citations since its posting on bioRxiv. It has successfully transitioned to formal publication in a prestigious journal, emphasizing the importance of its findings in the field of neurogenesis and cilia biology.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research, authored by Sandii Constable and collaborators from key institutions including Howard Hughes Medical Institute and The University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, explores the crucial roles of cilia in cerebellar granule cell neurogenesis. Following its initial presentation as a preprint, it has successfully advanced to peer-reviewed publication, further validating its research insights. The initial preprint has been cited 13 times, reflecting a robust engagement from the academic community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work's relevance is illustrated by its citations in notable venues such as Trends in Neurosciences, Current Biology, and The Journal of Cell Biology. This broad citing landscape underscores its impact on related fields, indicating that the findings contribute valuable insights to ongoing discourse surrounding cellular mechanisms in neurogenesis. Notably, this research has also attracted international attention, with citations from researchers based in the United States, Norway, Germany, and Turkey.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Beyond academia, the authors' commitment to open science is evident through their decision to share early findings on bioRxiv. This early sharing facilitated immediate community engagement, demonstrating the importance of timely dissemination in fostering scientific dialogue. While direct public mentions were not reported, the strong academic reception speaks to the critical nature of the work in advancing knowledge about cilia maintenance and its implications in neurodevelopmental processes.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The implications of this research extend into practical domains, given that the investigation of cilia loss is pivotal in understanding various neurodevelopmental disorders. Given its proven downstream reuse, this work has laid the groundwork for additional studies, enabling researchers to explore new avenues in cell biology and neurogenesis. In summary, this research not only contributes significantly to our fundamental understanding of cerebellar granule cell development but also sets the stage for future investigations that could lead to innovative therapeutic strategies.</p>",
